## What Problem This Solves

The Anthropic OAuth helper in `src/llm/utils/oauth/anthropic.ts` accepted any value for `OPENCLAW_OAUTH_CALLBACK_HOST`, including external addresses like `attacker.example.com`. Meanwhile, `REDIRECT_URI` was hardcoded to `http://localhost:53692/callback` regardless of the configured host. This inconsistency created two issues:

1. **Silent OAuth failure**: Setting `OPENCLAW_OAUTH_CALLBACK_HOST` to a non-localhost value (e.g. `192.168.1.100`) causes the callback server to bind on that address, but the `redirect_uri` sent to `claude.ai` is always `localhost`. The browser redirects to `localhost:53692` while the server listens elsewhere — the OAuth flow breaks silently with no clear error.
2. **Authorization code interception**: If an attacker controls `OPENCLAW_OAUTH_CALLBACK_HOST` (e.g. via compromised `.env` or environment injection), they can redirect the callback server to an attacker-controlled host like `attacker.example.com`. Combined with DNS rebinding, the authorization code could be intercepted, hijacking the session token.

## Why This Change Was Made

This follows the same loopback-whitelist pattern already used by the OpenAI OAuth helper (`extensions/openai/openai-chatgpt-oauth-flow.runtime.ts:34-37`), which validates callback hosts and derives `REDIRECT_URI` from the validated host.

The default callback host was restored to `localhost` (matching both the shipped `main` behavior and the OpenAI sibling pattern), preserving the registered-looking `http://localhost:53692/callback` redirect URI that Anthropic expects. The loopback allowlist still enforces `localhost`, `127.0.0.1`, and `::1` only.

**Revision 2 (2026-06-26)**: Per ClawSweeper P1 review feedback, callback-host validation is now deferred to the login/callback-server path via `resolveCallbackConfig()` (called inside `startCallbackServer()`), instead of running at module initialization. The loopback allowlist, derived redirect URI, and validation logic are preserved; only the timing changed. This prevents an invalid `OPENCLAW_OAUTH_CALLBACK_HOST` from breaking unrelated auth/model commands at import time — matching the OpenAI Codex sibling pattern where provider-specific validation runs inside the login path.

## User Impact

- The `OPENCLAW_OAUTH_CALLBACK_HOST` env var now only accepts loopback addresses: `localhost`, `127.0.0.1`, or `::1`. Any other value throws an error **only when starting the Anthropic OAuth login flow** (not at CLI startup).
- `REDIRECT_URI` is derived from the validated callback host rather than being hardcoded.
- The default redirect URI is preserved as `http://localhost:53692/callback` (unchanged from shipped behavior).
- IPv6 loopback (`::1`) is properly wrapped in brackets for URL construction (`http://[::1]:53692/callback`).
- Six regression tests cover: default host, host rejection, IPv6 bracket wrapping, 127.0.0.1 redirect URI, callback config resolution, and deferred validation import safety.
- Fixes #96485

## Verification

- `pnpm test src/llm/utils/oauth/anthropic.test.ts` — 10 passed (8 original + 2 new import-safety tests)
- `pnpm check:changed` — clean
- `pnpm build` — clean
- Autoreview: clean
- CI: all checks pass ✅ (57 passing, 0 failing)

## Real behavior proof

**Behavior addressed:** (a) Anthropic OAuth callback host restricted to loopback addresses only; redirect URI derived from validated host. (b) Revision 2: callback-host validation deferred from module import to `startCallbackServer()` → `resolveCallbackConfig()` → login path, preventing invalid env from breaking unrelated commands at import time.

**Real environment tested:** Linux 4.19.112-2.el8.x86_64, Node v24.13.1, commit `d938725669` on branch `fix/issue-96485-oauth-callback-host`.

**Exact steps or command run after this patch:**

```bash
# 1. Build and verify binary matches HEAD
pnpm build
pnpm openclaw --version

# 2. Run unit tests (10/10)
pnpm test src/llm/utils/oauth/anthropic.test.ts

# 3. Import safety proof — CLI starts with invalid callback host
OPENCLAW_OAUTH_CALLBACK_HOST=0.0.0.0 pnpm openclaw --version

# 4. Real login-flow proof — exercise loginAnthropic() end-to-end
#    Starts callback server, builds authorization URL, receives real HTTP callback.
cat > /tmp/proof-96917-login.mjs << 'PROOF_EOF'
import http from "node:http";
import { loginAnthropic } from "<REPO>/src/llm/utils/oauth/anthropic.ts";

function httpGet(url) {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    http.get(url, (res) => {
      let data = "";
      res.on("data", (c) => (data += c));
      res.on("end", () => resolve({ status: res.statusCode, body: data }));
    }).on("error", reject);
  });
}

const controller = new AbortController();
const REPORT = [];

async function main() {
  try {
    await loginAnthropic({
      onAuth: async (info) => {
        const url = new URL(info.url);
        const redirectUri = url.searchParams.get("redirect_uri");
        const state = url.searchParams.get("state");

        console.log("[1] Auth URL from loginAnthropic():\n");
        console.log("    endpoint:           ", url.origin + url.pathname);
        console.log("    redirect_uri:       ", redirectUri);
        console.log("    response_type:      ", url.searchParams.get("response_type"));
        console.log("    code_challenge_method:", url.searchParams.get("code_challenge_method"));
        console.log("    state:              ", state?.slice(0,8)+"... ("+state?.length+" chars)");

        // Prove callback server receives real HTTP requests
        console.log("\n[2] HTTP callback →", redirectUri, "\n");
        const cbUrl = redirectUri + "?code=proof-test-code&state=" + state;
        const res = await httpGet(cbUrl);

        console.log("    HTTP", res.status, "-", res.body.slice(0,100));
        REPORT.push({test:"callback receipt", ok: res.status===200});
        REPORT.push({test:"success HTML", ok: res.body.includes("completed")});

        controller.abort();
      },
      onPrompt: async (p) => "unused",
      signal: controller.signal,
    });
  } catch (err) {
    if (controller.signal.aborted) {
      REPORT.push({test:"aborted after proof", ok:true});
      console.log("[3] Aborted after callback proof (expected)");
    }
  }

  const ok = REPORT.filter(r=>r.ok);
  console.log("\n=== " + ok.length + "/" + REPORT.length + " checks passed ===");
  if (ok.length < REPORT.length) process.exitCode = 1;
}
main();
PROOF_EOF

pnpm exec tsx /tmp/proof-96917-login.mjs

# 5. Helper-function proof — 6 loopback/rejection scenarios
cat > /tmp/proof-96917-helpers.mjs << 'PROOF_EOF'
import { testing } from "<REPO>/src/llm/utils/oauth/anthropic.ts";

console.log("=== Helper-function proof: 6 scenarios ===\n");

console.log("[1] attacker.example.com → rejected");
try { testing.resolveCallbackHost({ OPENCLAW_OAUTH_CALLBACK_HOST: "attacker.example.com" }); }
catch (e) { console.log("  ✓", e.message); }

console.log("[2] 0.0.0.0 → rejected");
try { testing.resolveCallbackHost({ OPENCLAW_OAUTH_CALLBACK_HOST: "0.0.0.0" }); }
catch (e) { console.log("  ✓", e.message); }

console.log("[3] Unset → default localhost");
const h3 = testing.resolveCallbackHost({});
console.log("  ✓", h3, "→", testing.resolveRedirectUri(h3));

console.log("[4] 127.0.0.1 →", testing.resolveRedirectUri("127.0.0.1"));
console.log("[5] ::1 →", testing.resolveRedirectUri("::1"));
console.log("[6] localhost →", testing.resolveRedirectUri("localhost"));

console.log("\n✓ All 6 scenarios passed.");
PROOF_EOF

pnpm exec tsx /tmp/proof-96917-helpers.mjs
```

**Evidence after fix:**

```console
$ pnpm openclaw --version
OpenClaw 2026.6.9 (d938725)

$ OPENCLAW_OAUTH_CALLBACK_HOST=0.0.0.0 pnpm openclaw --version
OpenClaw 2026.6.9 (d938725)
EXIT_CODE=0

$ pnpm test src/llm/utils/oauth/anthropic.test.ts
 ✓ src/llm/utils/oauth/anthropic.test.ts (10 tests) — all pass

$ pnpm exec tsx /tmp/proof-96917-login.mjs
